<TITLE> Kosovo parliament votes on governing coalition </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PRISTINA, Serbia, Jan 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Kosovo's parliament sat on Wednesday to vote on a coalition government headed by ex-guerrilla Hashim Thaci on a promise to lead the province to independence from Serbia early this year. Thaci's Democratic Party of Kosovo (PDK) and the Democratic League of Kosovo (LDK) will share power after the PDK beat the once-dominant LDK into second place in a November parliamentary election. Thaci says the Albanian-majority province, administered by the United Nations since 1999, will declare independence with Western backing within weeks or months, after talks with Serbia to decide its fate ended in December in deadlock. The 90 percent Albanian majority is counting on the West to overrule opposition from Serbia and Russia and recognise Kosovo as the last state to be carved from the former Yugoslavia. Addressing parliament, the UN's Kosovo governor Joachim Ruecker said there was broad international agreement "that the status quo in Kosovo is no longer acceptable and that Kosovo's status needs to be resolved as soon as possible." The Democratic Party of 39-year-old Thaci emerged from the ranks of the guerrilla army that battled Serb forces in 1998-99, eclipsing the LDK's policy of passive resistance to a decade of repression under late Serb strongman Slobodan Milosevic. Western diplomats hope a broad coalition of the PDK and Kosovo President Fatmir Sejdiu's LDK will steer Kosovo through what promises to be a turbulent transition to statehood after Russia blocked its secession at the UN Security Council. The parliament, where the two parties together hold 62 seats, is also expected to re-elect Sejdiu for a new five-year term as president under the coalition deal. NATO bombed for 11 weeks in 1999 to halt the killing and ethnic cleansing of Albanians in a two-year Serb counter-insurgency war. Serb forces pulled out and Kosovo has been run by the United Nations and patrolled by NATO since, but the West fears that continuing its limbo